00:05:44.580 --> 00:05:45.560
What is this library?

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:49.860
So it's intended as a compatibility layer

00:05:49.990 --> 00:05:51.440
between different data frame libraries.

00:05:52.120 --> 00:05:55.380
So narwhals does not do any computation itself.

00:05:55.860 --> 00:05:59.360
It's more just a wrapper around different data frame APIs.

00:06:00.460 --> 00:06:02.000
And I like the Polars API,

00:06:02.170 --> 00:06:05.839
so I figured that I should keep it fairly close to the Polars API

00:06:05.860 --> 00:06:08.400
and in particular to Polars expressions.

00:06:09.460 --> 00:06:15.000
As to why novels, so I was just getting frustrated with the fact that,

00:06:17.220 --> 00:06:21.040
let's say about a year ago, there were relatively few libraries that supported Polars.

00:06:22.180 --> 00:06:27.720
And if libraries did support Polars, it was often just done by converting to Pandas

00:06:27.840 --> 00:06:29.220
or converting to PyArrow.

00:06:30.340 --> 00:06:34.220
Yet a lot of these libraries, they weren't doing anything that complicated with data frames.

00:06:35.080 --> 00:06:38.660
a lot of data frame consuming libraries, they don't really want to do that much.

00:06:39.020 --> 00:06:42.200
They want to select columns. They want to select rows.

00:06:42.460 --> 00:06:43.880
Maybe they want to do some aggregations.

00:06:44.360 --> 00:06:47.540
They're not doing stuff that's completely wild.

00:06:48.400 --> 00:06:53.180
And so trying to design some minimal compatibility layer,

00:06:53.600 --> 00:06:58.120
I think is a lot easier than trying to make a full-blown data frame API

00:06:58.540 --> 00:07:00.140
that end users are meant to use.

00:07:00.640 --> 00:07:03.160
So the idea with Narwhals is this is a tool for tool builders.

00:07:03.640 --> 00:07:15.380
If library maintainers want to support different data frame libraries as inputs with minimal overhead and with minimal maintenance required on their side, this is the problem we're trying to solve.

00:07:17.160 --> 00:07:26.080
It's a great problem to be solved because maybe you want to have a library that works with an abstract concept of a data frame.

00:07:27.240 --> 00:07:32.220
But usually I would imagine you have to start out and say, are we going to go and support Polars?

00:07:32.560 --> 00:07:33.860
Are we going to support pandas?

00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:38.800
And the APIs are different, not just the APIs, but the behaviors.

00:07:39.180 --> 00:07:44.840
For example, the lazy execution of Polars versus the eager execution of pandas.

00:07:45.540 --> 00:07:50.880
And so being able to just write your library so it takes either is probably a big hassle, right?

