00:46:24.260 --> 00:46:26.780
without you having to go through the data frame interchange protocol.

00:46:27.520 --> 00:46:28.700
Oh, yeah. Very nice. Okay.

00:46:30.740 --> 00:46:32.760
You mentioned the overhead before, but you do have a picture.

00:46:33.300 --> 00:46:34.280
Picture is always fun.

00:46:36.340 --> 00:46:41.960
In the picture, you've got little different operations, different times for each of the operations.

00:46:42.190 --> 00:46:48.300
And there's a quite small overhead for pandas versus pandas with narwhals.

00:46:49.620 --> 00:46:50.220
Yeah, exactly.

00:46:50.380 --> 00:46:53.520
Like in some of them, you can see it becoming a little bit faster.

00:46:53.690 --> 00:46:55.660
In some of them, you can see it becoming a little bit slower.

00:46:56.540 --> 00:47:01.860
And these are queries that I think are the size that you can expect most data scientists to be working with a lot of the time.

00:47:02.020 --> 00:47:05.740
You've got queries that take between a couple of seconds to 30 seconds.

00:47:07.620 --> 00:47:12.200
And it's pretty hard to distinguish reliably between the blue and red dots.

00:47:12.580 --> 00:47:15.620
Sometimes one's higher, sometimes the other one's higher.

00:47:16.240 --> 00:47:19.940
There's a bit of statistical variance just between running the same benchmark multiple times.

00:47:20.580 --> 00:47:23.040
But overall, yeah, we were pretty happy with these results.

00:47:25.000 --> 00:47:25.540
Yeah, that's great.

00:47:29.380 --> 00:47:31.840
So how well have we covered how it works?

00:47:32.080 --> 00:47:39.880
We talked about the API, but I know we've talked about the implementation of how you actually...

00:47:40.370 --> 00:47:43.020
Why is it basically almost the same speed?

00:47:43.460 --> 00:47:44.320
Why are you not doing it?

00:47:44.350 --> 00:47:45.060
Why is it not more working?

00:47:45.960 --> 00:47:47.820
Are you using underwater unicorn magic?

00:47:48.480 --> 00:47:49.140
Is that what it is?

00:47:49.940 --> 00:47:50.660
That's the secret, yes.

00:47:51.020 --> 00:47:51.920
Underwater unicorn magic.

00:47:52.340 --> 00:47:56.020
Well, perhaps first I should just say why we wrote this, how it works.

00:47:56.280 --> 00:47:59.500
And it's because really I want this to be a community-driven project.

00:48:00.460 --> 00:48:05.420
And this is one of those cases where open source is more of a social game than a technical one.

00:48:05.800 --> 00:48:07.000
I'm not saying that's always the case.

00:48:07.200 --> 00:48:09.140
There are many problems that are purely technical.

00:48:09.780 --> 00:48:11.620
Now else is a social game in the end.

00:48:12.100 --> 00:48:13.520
Like what we're doing isn't that complicated.

00:48:14.460 --> 00:48:18.760
But if we want it to work, then it needs to be accessible to the community.

00:48:19.360 --> 00:48:20.820
People do need to be able to trust us.

00:48:22.020 --> 00:48:24.700
And that typically does not happen if it's a one-person project.

00:48:25.440 --> 00:48:29.780
So it was really important to me that different people would be able to contribute to it.

00:48:30.280 --> 00:48:32.600
that it will be as simple and clear as possible.

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:35.720
So I made this page trying to explain how it works.

00:48:35.960 --> 00:48:39.340
It's not quite as clear and quite as extensive as it'd

00:48:39.340 --> 00:48:41.780
like to be, but a few contributors did say

00:48:41.800 --> 00:48:42.760
that it really helped them.

00:48:43.240 --> 00:48:46.080
So in terms of how do we get this slow overhead,

00:48:46.400 --> 00:48:48.160
so we're just defining an expression

00:48:48.340 --> 00:48:49.860
as being a function from a data frame

00:48:50.420 --> 00:48:52.780
to a sequence of series, and then we're just repeatedly

00:48:53.020 --> 00:48:54.680
and strictly applying that definition.

00:48:55.380 --> 00:48:57.100
So there's nothing too fancy going on.

00:48:58.520 --> 00:49:04.060
That's like in the end, just evaluating Lambda functions

00:49:04.200 --> 00:49:07.300
in Python, going down the stack trace, it's pretty fast.

00:49:07.620 --> 00:49:08.700
Yeah, that's really cool.

00:49:09.300 --> 00:49:11.140
Yeah, so people can check this out if they want to know.

00:49:11.540 --> 00:49:13.920
I think this might be where I saw the pandas-like expression.

00:49:14.380 --> 00:49:15.000
Ah, right, yeah.

00:49:15.440 --> 00:49:18.820
Yeah, pandas-like, it's this class that encompasses pandas mode

00:49:18.960 --> 00:49:21.640
in QDF, the ones that kind of follow the pandas API.

00:49:22.620 --> 00:49:24.820
Yeah, close enough for what you need to do.

00:49:25.720 --> 00:49:26.520
Yeah, exactly.

00:49:28.240 --> 00:49:35.800
All right. Well, I saw a question out there in the audience somewhere from Francesco,

00:49:36.340 --> 00:49:41.140
which was basically asking about the roadmap. Where are you? Where are you going?

00:49:41.780 --> 00:49:46.420
Yeah, I should probably introduce Francesco. He's one of the most active contributors to

00:49:46.560 --> 00:49:53.759
the project. So thanks, Francesco, for helping to make it a success. He was actually also

00:49:53.780 --> 00:49:56.680
the first person to adopt narwhals in one of his libraries.

00:49:59.220 --> 00:50:02.360
Yeah, I spoke to him about it at a conference, and he was like, I've got this tiny little

00:50:03.560 --> 00:50:06.640
time-based CV library, let's try narwhalifying it as an experiment.

00:50:07.540 --> 00:50:08.960
And sure, we did that then.

00:50:10.880 --> 00:50:12.800
Not scikit-learn, sorry, not there yet.

00:50:13.580 --> 00:50:18.359
scikit-lego, which was this kind of experimental building blocks for scikit-learn pipelines that he

00:50:18.260 --> 00:50:26.960
maintains, and then we've just been taking it from there. So in terms of roadmap, my top priority is

00:50:27.040 --> 00:50:33.180
helping out libraries that have shown interest in narwhals. So at the moment, Formulaic, that opened

00:50:33.280 --> 00:50:37.360
a draft pull request in which they were trying out narwhals, and they tagged me just about some

00:50:37.860 --> 00:50:43.880
things they were missing, so I'd like to see if I can take that to completion. I've got, I think

00:50:43.700 --> 00:50:44.740
I think I've got most of it working,

00:50:45.440 --> 00:50:47.580
but just been a bit busy with conferences recently.

00:50:48.520 --> 00:50:52.140
So maybe next month I'll be able to get something ready for review

00:50:52.250 --> 00:50:53.080
and show that to them.

00:50:53.460 --> 00:50:54.480
That would be pretty cool.

