in adding extra methods and adding extra backends and things.

00:53:36.200 --> 00:53:39.960
So I'm trying to leave a lot of that to the community.

00:53:40.700 --> 00:53:41.500
So like with Dask,

00:53:41.510 --> 00:53:44.600
I just got the rough building blocks together.

00:53:45.380 --> 00:53:46.240
And then it was just so nice,

00:53:46.440 --> 00:53:49.040
like so many really high quality contributions coming up

00:53:49.220 --> 00:53:53.100
that brought the Dask support pretty much complete.

00:53:53.150 --> 00:53:54.840
We should see now if we're able to execute

00:53:54.950 --> 00:53:57.120
all of the TPCH queries with the Dask backend,

00:53:57.360 --> 00:53:59.360
we might actually be there

00:53:59.380 --> 00:54:01.340
or be pretty close to getting there.

00:54:01.980 --> 00:54:02.480
Nice.

00:54:02.820 --> 00:54:06.300
What does TPC-H stand for?

00:54:07.180 --> 00:54:09.020
I don't remember what it stands for,

00:54:09.140 --> 00:54:11.360
but it's a set of database queries

00:54:12.120 --> 00:54:14.620
that they were originally written for testing out

00:54:14.740 --> 00:54:15.960
different databases.

00:54:16.450 --> 00:54:18.400
So it's a bunch of SQL queries.

00:54:19.280 --> 00:54:23.820
But I'm not sure if it was Kaggle that popularized--

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:26.560
not Kaggle, sorry, not Kaggle-- if it was

00:54:26.580 --> 00:54:30.240
that popularized the idea of translating these SQL queries

00:54:30.600 --> 00:54:34.240
to data frame-like APIs and then running different data frames

00:54:34.450 --> 00:54:36.920
on them to see who wins the speed test.

00:54:37.300 --> 00:54:40.300
But we just figured-- they do a bunch of things

00:54:40.370 --> 00:54:45.440
like joins, concatenations, filtering, comparisons with dates,

00:54:45.820 --> 00:54:46.620
string operations.

00:54:46.790 --> 00:54:50.700
And we're like, OK, if the narwhals API is able to do all of this,

00:54:51.030 --> 00:54:53.260
then maybe it's extensive enough to be useful.

00:54:53.880 --> 00:55:02.080
Right. Yeah, yeah. That's super cool. It sounds a little bit like the TOB index plus other stuff, maybe, but for databases.

00:55:04.260 --> 00:55:05.600
I'm not familiar with that.

00:55:05.640 --> 00:55:15.260
It's like a language ranking type of thing. And, you know, one aspect is maybe ranking the databases. But yeah, no, this is very cool. Okay. Got it.

00:55:16.599 --> 00:55:22.660
In the end, we're not trying to be fast as novels, but we just want to make sure that there's no extra overhead.

00:55:23.240 --> 00:55:28.460
Exactly. As long as you're not much slower than the stuff that you're operating with,

00:55:28.920 --> 00:55:33.600
that's all you should ask for. You can't make it go faster in the extreme. You did talk about

00:55:33.670 --> 00:55:38.680
some optimizations, but you can't fundamentally change what's happening. Yeah, we could do some

00:55:38.920 --> 00:55:43.100
optimizations on the novel side, but to be honest, I'm not sure I want to. And part of the reason is

00:55:43.220 --> 00:55:49.280
because I want this to be a pretty simple project that's easy to maintain. And that's really just

00:55:49.300 --> 00:55:49.740
slow overhead.

00:55:52.019 --> 00:55:53.940
Add extra docs and tutorials coming.

00:55:54.960 --> 00:55:55.340
That's fun.

00:55:56.240 --> 00:55:57.260
Are you looking for contributors

00:55:57.370 --> 00:55:59.680
who maybe want to write some tutorials or docs?

00:56:00.420 --> 00:56:01.320
I would love this, yeah.

00:56:01.370 --> 00:56:03.660
I mean, it drives me crazy when I see so many projects

00:56:03.800 --> 00:56:05.180
where people have put so much effort

00:56:05.770 --> 00:56:07.000
into making a really good product,

00:56:07.220 --> 00:56:08.880
but then the documentation is really scant.

00:56:09.380 --> 00:56:13.360
Like, if you don't prioritize writing good docs,

00:56:13.500 --> 00:56:15.080
nobody's going to use your product.

00:56:15.840 --> 00:56:19.460
So I was really grateful to my company.

00:56:19.520 --> 00:56:22.520
They had four interns come on who really helped out

00:56:22.600 --> 00:56:25.080
with making the docs look amazing.

00:56:25.220 --> 00:56:25.780
Oh, that's cool.

00:56:25.960 --> 00:56:27.580
Like if you look at the API reference,

00:56:28.080 --> 00:56:32.800
I think every single function now has got a doc string

00:56:33.280 --> 00:56:35.140
with an example at the bottom.

00:56:35.180 --> 00:56:36.360
I think there's API reference.

00:56:37.020 --> 00:56:38.580
Yeah, if you search for any function in here,

00:56:39.480 --> 00:56:41.860
yeah, in the search box at the top,

00:56:41.940 --> 00:56:44.940
some, I don't know, series dot something.

00:56:46.260 --> 00:56:48.780
for any of these, we've got an example of,

00:56:48.920 --> 00:56:51.180
here's how you could write a data frame agnostic function

00:56:51.380 --> 00:56:53.700
which uses this method.

00:56:54.280 --> 00:56:56.380
Let's show that if you pass pandas or polars,

00:56:56.510 --> 00:56:57.800
you get the same result.

00:56:58.420 --> 00:56:59.740
And if there's some slight differences

00:57:00.020 --> 00:57:01.220
that we just cannot get around,

00:57:01.540 --> 00:57:03.120
like in the way that they handle missing values,

00:57:03.720 --> 00:57:05.720
then we've got a very clear note about in the docs.

00:57:06.220 --> 00:57:06.920
Yeah, that's great.

00:57:10.560 --> 00:57:12.320
Maybe someday support for DuckDB?

00:57:13.520 --> 00:57:19.300
I would like that. I don't think we have much of a choice about whether or not we support DuckDB.

00:57:19.640 --> 00:57:23.860
DuckDB is really on fire now. It really is.

00:57:24.620 --> 00:57:30.380
Yeah, I think it might be a question of either we have some level of support for DuckDB,

00:57:31.040 --> 00:57:34.180
or somebody else is going to make something like Narwhals that supports DuckDB,

00:57:34.440 --> 00:57:42.860
and then we become extinct. But besides, to be honest, DuckDB is amazing.

00:57:43.280 --> 00:57:46.380
I just find it a bit painful to write SQL strings.

00:57:46.690 --> 00:57:53.080
And so if I could use DuckDB, but with the Polars API that I prefer and I'm more familiar with, then...

00:57:53.840 --> 00:57:55.920
Yeah, I 100% agree.

00:57:56.820 --> 00:58:02.940
It looks super nice, but if you look, it has a SQL example, and then the Python example is just SQL, quote, quote, quote.

00:58:03.380 --> 00:58:03.780
Yeah, exactly.

00:58:04.020 --> 00:58:06.080
Here's the SQL embedded in Python, you know what I mean?

00:58:06.230 --> 00:58:08.760
So you're kind of writing SQL no matter what.

00:58:09.540 --> 00:58:11.880
Yeah, and then the error messages that you get sometimes are like,

00:58:12.020 --> 00:58:14.080
oh, there's a pass error near this keyword.

00:58:14.190 --> 00:58:15.900
And you're like, what on earth is going on?

00:58:17.300 --> 00:58:18.380
And then you're like, oh, yeah, I forgot.

00:58:18.900 --> 00:58:21.300
I forgot an extra comma at the end of my select or something.

00:58:21.370 --> 00:58:21.680
I don't know.

00:58:22.480 --> 00:58:27.060
So DuckDB is a little bit like SQLite,

00:58:27.900 --> 00:58:30.780
but for analytics rather than relational maybe.

00:58:31.150 --> 00:58:33.140
I'm not sure if that's a good summary.

00:58:33.140 --> 00:58:35.720
I think it's primarily aimed at analysts.

00:58:36.010 --> 00:58:38.400
Yeah, analytical kinds of things.

00:58:38.490 --> 00:58:40.120
Yeah, data scientists and people.

00:58:40.270 --> 00:58:41.980
What I kind of...

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:45.820
What we are going to struggle with is that in DuckDB,

00:58:46.040 --> 00:58:48.840
there's no guarantees about row order or operations.

00:58:50.980 --> 00:58:54.360
But on the plus side, when I look at what Altair are doing with data frames,

00:58:54.620 --> 00:58:57.820
when I look at some of the other libraries that I've shown interest in nowles,

00:58:58.640 --> 00:59:00.500
they're often just doing very simple things.

00:59:00.720 --> 00:59:02.700
They're not doing things that depend on row order.

00:59:03.230 --> 00:59:07.120
So if we could just initially just support DuckDB for the operations

00:59:07.460 --> 00:59:08.700
that don't require row order,

00:59:09.180 --> 00:59:11.380
so for something like a cumulative sum,

00:59:11.980 --> 00:59:14.380
maybe initially we just don't support that for DuckDB.

00:59:15.840 --> 00:59:18.280
Like in the end, if you want to do advanced SQL,

00:59:18.500 --> 00:59:19.900
just use DuckDB directly.

00:59:20.920 --> 00:59:24.820
As I said earlier, I don't recommend that end users use novels directly,

00:59:25.060 --> 00:59:28.880
but even just having some common operations,

00:59:29.600 --> 00:59:31.640
ones that aren't row order dependent,

00:59:31.900 --> 00:59:33.540
I'd like to think that this is already enough

00:59:34.300 --> 00:59:36.500
to solve some real problems for real people.

00:59:37.640 --> 00:59:40.200
Yeah, I know you said it's mostly for library builders,

00:59:40.440 --> 00:59:44.360
but if you were building an app and you were not committed to your data frame library,

00:59:45.240 --> 00:59:49.320
or you really wanted to leave open the possibility of choosing a different data frame library,

00:59:50.220 --> 00:59:55.180
you know, sort of using narwhals to isolate that a little bit might be nice, right?

00:59:55.920 --> 01:00:04.940
Yeah. So, yeah. Yeah. If anyone tries to do this, and I'd love to hear your story. I did hear from

01:00:05.580 --> 01:00:09.760
somebody in our community call. We've got a community call every two weeks, by the way,

01:00:09.840 --> 01:00:11.760
if anyone wants to come and chat with us.

01:00:12.300 --> 01:00:13.960
I did hear from somebody that, like, at work,

01:00:14.120 --> 01:00:16.840
has got some teams that are primarily using Pandas,

01:00:17.220 --> 01:00:19.440
some teams that are primarily using Polars,

01:00:19.660 --> 01:00:21.580
and he just wanted to build some common logic

01:00:21.860 --> 01:00:23.460
that both teams could use,

01:00:23.900 --> 01:00:25.420
and he was using narwhals for that.

01:00:26.400 --> 01:00:27.780
So I think there are some use cases

01:00:28.080 --> 01:00:29.700
beyond just library maintainers.

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:30.580
Yeah, absolutely.

01:00:30.840 --> 01:00:32.500
Maybe you're building just an internal library,

01:00:33.620 --> 01:00:36.600
and it needs to work with some code you've written in Pandas,

01:00:36.780 --> 01:00:39.300
but maybe you want to try your new project in Polars.

01:00:39.980 --> 01:00:41.240
but you want to still use that library, right?

